{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n`test_code_review_ws5.py::test_security_rule_yaml_files_are_present_and_nonempty` (`:36-39`)\nonly checks one file is non-empty and greps another for the substrings `rebar.builtin.security.`\nand `rules:`. Invalid YAML, duplicate ids, malformed rule objects, wrong severities, or an\nunusable pattern all satisfy it. VALIDATED.\n\n## Definitions (make the ACs concrete)\n- **Rule family** = one vendored security-rule YAML file under\n  `src/rebar/grounding/detectors/builtin/`. There are three security families:\n  `security_iac_public_exposure.yaml`, `security_owasp_cwe.yaml`,\n  `security_secrets_gitleaks.yaml`.\n- **Loaded via the production loader** = through `rebar.grounding.detectors.registry`\n  (`load_registry` / the file-level `_detectors_from_file`), which returns `Detector`\n  objects (id, backend, namespace, envelope, rule) â€” NOT hand-parsed YAML.\n- **Fails closed (observable)** = when a family file is malformed (invalid YAML, or a rule\n  missing its required `id`), the production loader yields ZERO detectors FROM THAT FILE and\n  records the loss (an entry in `Registry.parse_drops`, or the specific rule dropped) â€” the\n  loss is SURFACED, never silently masked as a working registry that omits the rule. The test\n  asserts both the absence of the detector and the recorded drop.\n\n## What\nReplace the substring/presence assertions with loader-based behavioral checks:\n1. Load the registry via `load_registry` (built-in dir) and, for each of the three security\n   families, assert the EXACT set of detector ids contributed by that file, their `backend`,\n   and their declared severity (from the rule/envelope metadata) match expected values â€”\n   pinning the real loaded contract, not a substring.\n2. Fail-closed: build a temp built-in dir containing a DELIBERATELY malformed copy of a family\n   file (broken YAML and, separately, a rule with its `id` removed), load it through the\n   production loader, and assert (a) no detector from that file appears in the registry and\n   (b) the drop is recorded in `Registry.parse_drops` (broken YAML) / the rule is absent\n   (missing id) â€” proving malformed vendored data does not silently produce a usable detector.\n3. Keep a fast presence/freshness guard ONLY if explicitly labeled as such (not the coverage\n   claim).\n\nNote: matcher EXECUTION (running opengrep/ast-grep against positive/negative code snippets)\nis NOT asserted here because it requires the external backend binary, which is not guaranteed\nin unit CI; this ticket pins the loaded rule CONTRACT (ids/backends/severities) and the\nfail-closed loader behavior, which are the untested gaps. (Matcher execution is exercised\nelsewhere where the backend is available.)\n\n## Scope\n- `tests/unit/test_code_review_ws5.py` â€” loader-based id/backend/severity assertions + the\n  fail-closed malformed-data test.\n- `src/rebar/grounding/detectors/builtin/` â€” reference only (validated, not modified).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] For each of the three security families, the test loads it via the production\n      `load_registry` and asserts the exact detector ids, their backends, and their severities.\n- [ ] A fail-closed test feeds malformed vendored data (broken YAML; and a rule with no `id`)\n      through the production loader and asserts the detector is ABSENT and the loss is recorded\n      (`parse_drops` / dropped rule) â€” not silently loaded.\n- [ ] The old substring/presence-only assertion is removed (or explicitly relabeled as a fast\n      freshness guard, distinct from the coverage claim).\n- [ ] `make test` green."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783804147751755001,"uuid":"70213c3d-7152-43a1-b609-21f971320284"}